      "message": "It\u0027s pretty wacky. For example, `global` looks like a statement, but it\u0027s not really.\n\ng \u003d 1\n\ndef F():\n  print g\n  g \u003d 2\n  print g\n  global g\n\nwill happily print 1 and then 2 (though it might warn on recent-er interpreters). That\u0027s a side effect of the fact that it\u0027s really a matter of how the name is used through the *entirety* of the function. For example:\n\ndef F():\n  print x\n  x \u003d 2\n  print x\n\nwill be an Exception on the first `print x` because there *is* an assignment to `x` in the body, which implicitly makes `x` a local for the entire function (and there\u0027s no global declaration), and on the first print, it\u0027s not yet bound.\n\nConversely:\n\ndef F():\n  print x\n  Y(x)\n  # any other junk that doesn\u0027t assign to `x`...\n  print x\n\nis fine, and will refer to the module scope `x` (which is the case in the code we\u0027re talking about here).\n\nNow nest a few closures into the body of F() that refer to `x` and explicit variable declaration starts to sound like maybe not the worst idea ever.\n\nSo... it\u0027s sort of because it\u0027s only reads vs. being written to that global isn\u0027t required here.",
